17:<Original problem:
![enter image description here][1]

I think the point of this problem is to find the amount of money you "should" spend on advertising in order to sell the largest number of products, but this problem doesn't even ask for that. There is zero discussion of motivation, and really no reason to even read any of the words in this "word problem."


Revised:

Tell the students to get out a piece of paper, pick a number between 150 and 400, and write it down.

I now tell them, "You are a company that makes and sells t-shirts. Think of a name for your company and write it at the top of your page."

Once they have done that, I tell them that the number they wrote down is the amount of money that their company has. I tell them to put a dollar sign in front of it.

"Now, you need to make a bunch of shirts to sell. That costs 100 dollars, so subtract 100 from your budget. This what you have left over."

"Now that you have your shirts, the last thing you need to do is advertise them, so people know about your company and will buy your shirts. Choose how much money you want to spend on advertising from what you have left (you don't need to save money for anything else, but keep in mind that too much advertising isn't always good)."

"I am the time machine. Once you have decided what to spend on advertising, come up to me and tell me, and I'll fast forward one month and tell you how many shirts your company sold in its first month."

When students come up, I put their advertising dollars into the equation $N=-a^<zipRedac>+300a+6$, but don't tell them that's what I'm doing. I just tell them the result.

Now, I ask them to walk around and compare their sales figures with other people. See who sold the most shirts, and who sold the fewest. Try as a group to figure out what's the BEST amount to spend on advertising, to sell the most shirts.

I would then put a large set of axes on the board, x:[0,350], y:[0,<zipRedac>5000], and tell each student to come up and put a dot on the board that corresponds to the amount they spent, and the number of shirts they sold.

Only at this point would I give them the formula. I'd tell them that, using this graph, we have come up with an equation that shows how number of shirts sold depends on advertising dollars (or, depending on the class, actually try to fit a curve to the data). Find the maximum of this function to find the ideal amount to spend using our traditional methods (in the case of the "Business Calculus" class >
